e diarrhoea"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary indication for terlipressin is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebleeding oesophageal varices\u003C/strong\u003E. It acts as a vasoconstrictor in the splanchnic circulation, reducing portal pressure and therefore reducing bleeding from varices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefractory ascites\u003C/strong\u003E is managed with diuretics and paracentesis rather than vasoactive medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal ulcer bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E is typically managed with proton pump inhibitors and endoscopic therapy rather than vasoactive medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis\u003C/strong\u003E requires insulin, fluid replacement and electrolyte correction as its primary management strategy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute diarrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E requires fluid replacement and treatment of the underlying cause rather than vasoactive therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETerlipressin is particularly useful in the acute management of variceal bleeding as it can be administered while preparing for definitive endoscopic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Terlipressin is a vasopressin analogue primarily used to treat bleeding oesophageal varices in portal hypertension.","Terlipressin causes vasoconstriction of splanchnic vessels, reducing portal pressure and bleeding risk.","Terlipressin is more selective for vasopressin V1 receptors compared to vasopressin itself."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G 